COMPONENT NAME: IKM E-Business Suite (Open Interface) COMPONENT VERSION: 10.1.3.1 AUTHOR: Oracle COMPATIBILITY: ODI 10.1.3.5.0 and above
Description: - Integration Knowledge Module - Integrates data into an Oracle Application Open Interface target table in incremental update mode. - Inexistent rows are inserted; already existing rows are updated. - Data can be controlled. Invalid data is isolated in the Error Table and can be recycled. - When using this module with a journalized source table, it is possible to synchronize deletions.
Alternatively, this Knowledge Module allows you to store a group id value to use within several interfaces. To genearate and use a new group id , do the following: 1- Choose OA_CREATE_NEW_GROUP_ID 2- Give a name to the group id in OA_GROUP_ID_NAME 3- Provide a valid SQL expression to populate the group id value (sequ.nextval for example) in OA_GROUP_ID_EXPRESSION 4- In the mappings of the interface, choose UD1 for all the columns you want to populate with the value of the group id and populate these columns to a default value of 0.
To use an existing group id : 1- Choose OA_USE_EXISTING_GROUP_ID 2- Give the name of the group id to use in OA_GROUP_ID_NAME 3- In the mappings of the interface, choose UD1 for all the columns you want to populate with the value of the group id and populate these columns to a default value of 0.
Restrictions: - Comparison of data is made using the Update Key defined in the interface. It has to be set. - The TRUNCATE option cannot work if the target table is referenced by another table (foreign key) - The FLOW_CONTROL option calls the Knowledge Control Module to isolate the errors. If not set, an error occurs. - The option FLOW_TABLE_OPTION is set by default to NOLOGGING. Set it to whitespace if the interface runs on an Oracle 7 database - Deletes are commited regardless of the COMMIT option - The OA_CREATE_NEW_GROUP_ID option creates a table on the work schema of the interface to store the value of the current group.
Change History: MAY-2008 - Adapted default for KM option "Application List" - Validation added for OA_GROUP_ID_NAME - Validation added for OA_GROUP_ID_EXPRESSION
Automatically attempts to insert data into the Target Datastore of the Interface
Identifies and updates rows of the Target Datastore depending on the value of the UPDATE_KEY columns of the target datastore records.
Commit all data inserted or updated in the target datastore.
Check this option to synchronize journalized deletions. This option will take effect only if one source table is journalized in your interface.
Check this option if you wish to perform flow control.
Check this option to recycle data rejected from a previous control.
Check this option to control the target table after having inserted or updated target data.
Check this option if you wish to truncate the target datastore.
Check this option if you wish to delete all the rows of the target datastore.
Set this option to NO if you wish to retain temporary objects (tables, files and scripts) after integration. Useful for debugging.

Use this option to specify the attributes for the integration table at create time and used for increasing performance. This option is set by default to NOLOGGING (valid only from Oracle v8). This option may be left empty.

This option affects the use of PURGE key word and the way statistics are collected:
Values PURGE STATS 10 Yes DBMS_STATS 9 No DBMS_STATS 8 No ANALYZE

This option generates an extra validation step during development. Validations performed are: - validation of KM option COMPATIBLE - validation of RDBMS version of staging database - validation of KM option DETECTION_STRATEGY
This option should be turned off for all production use in particular for high-frequency execution. There is not added value in production, only processing overhead.

Valid values are - MINUS: MINUS clause is used when populating flow table in order to exclude records, which identically exist in target. - NOT_EXISTS:NOT EXISTS clause is used when populating flow table in order to exclude records, which identically exist in target. - POST_FLOW: all records from source are loaded into flow table. After that an update statement is used to flag all rows in flow table, which identically exist in target. - NONE: all records from source are loaded into flow table. All target records are updated even when target records is identical to flow table record.
Check this option if you wish to analyze the target table before loading data into the integration table.
Use this option to specify the hint to be used while loading the integration table.
Check this option if you want to submit Oracle Application Open Interface Program
Oracle Application User Name for context initialization
Oracle Application Responsibility to use for context initialization
Default language used for the responsibility
Oracle Application Name for this interface

Oracle Applications program arguments using this syntax : , argumentX => 'value' , argumentX => 'value' , ... If you are using CREATE_NEW_GROUP_ID or USE_EXISTING_GROUP_ID options, you can use v_group_id variable as argument. ex : , argumentX => 'value' , argumentX => v_group_id , ...
A group id name identifies records belonging to the same batch load across all tables of the Open Interface. OA_GROUP_ID_NAME uniquely identifies the current batch load.

A group id identifies records belonging to the same batch load across all tables of the Open Interface. OA_GROUP_ID_EXPRESSION returns a number to be used as group identifier. This number is stored until the Concurrent program is called for data import.
The expression is usually an Oracle sequence.
Create a new persistant group ID?
Check this option if you want to create a new group id and store it's value for future use
Check this option if you want to use the value of an existing group id, given its name (OA_GROUP_ID_NAME)
Check this option to remove the definition of the group ID at the end of the job
